 not only on the lessons of the past but also builds on Europe’s ability to protect its citizens against the power of global market forces. Framing its argument through the critical theory of the Frankfurt School, this volume will attract readers interested in political and social philosophy, collective memory studies, European studies, international relations and contemporary politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aCollective memory.  aCritical theory.  aEurocrisis.  aEurope.  aEuropean Union.  aFrankfurt School.  aHistorical Narratives.  aIntegration.  aRupture.  aTotal war.1 aVerovšek, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614311240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526143112423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526143112/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles